Epidemics in man, animals, plants - Zimbabwe 19950303.0097
Date: Wed, 20 Mar 2002
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Herald (Harare) via All Africa Global Media, 18 Mar 2002 [edited
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200203180895.html>

Officials warn of rabies outbreak in Mhondoro
----------------------------------------------
Officials have warned of a rabies outbreak in Mhondoro after a boy died and
4 other people were suspected to have come into contact with the virus
infected dogs last week. The cases were treated at Manyewe Clinic and Ngezi
Hospital, both in Mhondoro, but the boy died after admission at Harare
Central Hospital.
Rabies is an acute viral disease of the nervous system that is transmitted
by rabid dogs or jackals to humans. A patient who has contracted the rabies
virus becomes severely hydrophobic (fear of water), restless, and nervous.
Symptoms also include excess salivation and panting like a dog. Rabid
animals usually die after 10 days and symptoms in humans may appear within
5 days after exposure.
Acting head of the Disease Prevention and Control unit in the Ministry of
Health and Child Welfare Dr Stanley Midzi confirmed the 5 cases at the
weekend and warned people to be wary of dogs, especially stray ones that
were not likely to have been vaccinated. He said 3 of the victims were
vaccinated soon after exposure, while health officials were still following
up another boy who was bitten by the same dog that bit the boy who later died.
"We take all bites from dogs that have not been provoked as suspect because
we can only confirm rabies by testing the animals' brains. However, if a
person is bitten by any dog they should immediately seek treatment," said
Dr Midzi. He said he regretted that the shortage of foreign currency in the
country had disturbed regular dog vaccinations, which used to be conducted
by the Veterinary Services department.
Most dogs roaming the streets are not vaccinated and only a few people,
especially those living in low-density suburbs where there are facilities,
still vaccinate their dogs regularly against rabies at private centers.
--
