<promed@promedmail.org>
[The described case in Zimbabwe -- a country where urban rabies is known to
persist -- seems to be related to a delayed reporting of the exposure in a
boy, leading to his inevitable death.
According to the World Health Organization (WHO) fact sheet, where data are
available there appears to be consistency in the toll canine rabies exacts
on children in endemic communities. From age-stratified incidence rates, on
average between 30 per cent and 50 per cent of human cases of rabies (and
therefore rabies deaths) occur in children under 15 years of age. It is
also noteworthy that the more detailed age-stratified epidemiological
studies tend to suggest even higher childhood incidence rates (for example,
60 per cent). Furthermore, most of these bites are never reported and go
unrecognized by both parents and health officials. Consequently, exposed
children often do not receive timely and complete post-exposure treatment.
It is likely, therefore, that a disproportionately high number of young
children contract and die of undiagnosed rabies -- many more than even the
most pessimistic estimates suggest. See:
<http://www.who.int/emc/diseases/zoo/Canine%20Rabies%20in%20Children.pdf>.
During the 5 years 1994-1998, 26 clinically confirmed rabies cases in
humans have been reported to WHO by Zimbabwe, 12 of them laboratory
confirmed. Out of the 8 cases in humans reported in 1998 -- the last
reported year in the WHO tables -- 6 cases were caused by rabid dogs; the
source of the remaining 2 was unknown. During that year, 442 rabies cases
were confirmed by the laboratory in animals in Zimbabwe, including 159
dogs, 8 cats, 145 ruminants, 11 equines, and 119 wild animals - of which 3
were mongoose. - Mod.AS
